children.name: Text
children.value: The lookout loses them. Complacency sets in, when at first you appear to be catching them, but upon rounding a cape, you find they have vanished! Bright white settlements cluster the sound like a fairy circle, it seems they could have docked in any of them. "We have lost them!" a skeptic pipes up, "so what now?! Stick a pin in the map?! Solicit a friendly local power for help?!!"

children.name: Text
children.value: Study the map to guess their most likely docking point

children.name: Text
children.value: The navigator is as sure of himself as he can be in the circumstances. "If I were Pyrphorian, god help me, I would head for Montoya," his finger circles the large settlement, "it has a large marina where my devilish vessel might be easily concealed." Upon searching Montoya harbour, they indeed find the Pyrphorian ship in a secluded corner of mangrove. That being well, they must hope now they have not lost too much time.

children.name: Text
children.value: The navigator is as much as a failure as the lookout. Your ship makes a cat's cradle of the sound, as the navigator drags you hopelessly from one port to the next, almost at random. "Since you're so fine with directions," says the lieutenant to the diplomat in question, "perhaps you should explain where it was we went off course to Miss. Hannah Goode!"

children.name: Text
children.value: Entreat nearby local authorities for information

children.name: Text
children.value: You are made to wait in line. Your diplomats may have done well to remember this local crest as one loyal to the crown, but you are not the only envoys present. Daiquiris, bananas and soft furnishings are small compensation for the time lost. Despite these formalities, the prefect transpires to be loyal. He intimates that Montoya is the only nearby place he has knowledge of, that the Pyrphorians have their claws into. You cross fingers, and head there.

children.name: Text
children.value: "They must have been in league with the Pyrphorians!" wails your duped diplomat. Having failed to detect local complicity— rooted either in fear or allegiance— your diplomat insists you sail south along the coast. Your expedition continues diligently for three days in that direction without sighting a single human settlement. "Since you're so fine with words," says the lieutenant to the diplomat in question, "perhaps you should explain our failure to Miss. Hannah Goode!"

children.name: Text
children.value: The contract and those Pyrphorians must be here in Montoya, but where? The city sprawls before you under a pastel blue sky, the distinctive whitewall and terracotta of Imperial La Corona glowing softly all along the narrow estuary where the Mixcoatl meets the ocean. Yet, tranquil it is not. Anxiety is written in every passing face. They must know who you are and what you seek, but finding one brave enough to share is a different matter. You can ask around, or rely instead on your own eyes to find clues.

children.name: Text
children.value: Ask the local Montoyans if they know anything

children.name: Text
children.value: Your attaché hits it off with the harbourmaster, presenting you (not entirely falsely) as a fellow port official sympathetic to the Pyrphorian problem in the region. "I am sick of it," says the Montoyan, "whenever they come here it is a nightmare for us! If you take will action, it will be my pleasure to assist." Out on the sun-baked rooftop he points upriver. "There, at the casona." A large verdant ranch wavers in the distance, the sanctuary of the Pyrphorians.

children.name: Text
children.value: The only one who may be willing to help you is a Great Plainsman. The softly-spoken giant is hauling thick rope at the dock. "I would be putting my life at risk," he says gravely, looking over his shoulder. He seems to know something.

children.name: Text
children.value: A little recompense always calms the nerves

children.name: Text
children.value: The Great Plainsman looks nervously over your goods.

children.name: Text
children.value: "That should be enough to get me out of here," he says, inspecting the merchandise. "They have taken the big ranch for their gatherings. You'll need a lot more than this if you hoping to break in— see all these people? There's a reason they're afraid." You head for the ranch on the outskirts of Montoya, to where darkness awaits.

children.name: Text
children.value: "No!" he says, unwilling to risk his life for such scant reward. He glances around, sweeping back his long dark hair. It seems increasingly unlikely he will co-operate.

children.name: Text
children.value: He raises his hands, impressed, while remaining wary. "Perhaps you can be the ones to finally unseat them," he says, pointing upriver, "they have taken the big ranch for their gatherings. When you go there, expect trouble." He looks your soldiers up and down again, "even if you do seem prepared."

children.name: Text
children.value: "Seen enough of that in my lifetime," he says with quiet defiance. Your soldiers hang their heads— with the Pyrphorians here, Montoyans hardly need you stirring up more trouble. "If all you have to offer is violence, take it to those who deserve it," he says, gesturing at a decrepit-looking warehouse towards the end of the quay. Then he disappears without so much as a farewell.

children.name: Text
children.value: "Your envoy is right," he says, "I can cover my tracks well enough." He nods upriver. "They have taken the big ranch for their gatherings. You better be ready if you hope to break in— see all these people? There's a reason they're afraid." You head for the ranch on the outskirts of Montoya, to where darkness awaits.

children.name: Text
children.value: He sighs deeply and rolls his eyes. "If you can't convince me, good luck convincing them to stop what they have begun," he says, gesturing at a decrepit-looking warehouse at the end of the quay. Then he disappears without so much as a farewell.

children.name: Text
children.value: Your attaché's weepy plea is better received than anyone who had to hear it could have expected. "Of course we will help you stand against this terrible evil!" A local man says cheerfully, leading you to the end of the pier, where a rather decrepit warehouse stands. "This is it, we're all counting on you," he whispers encouragingly at the door, before hurrying away.

children.name: Text
children.value: Smash down the warehouse door and charge in

children.name: Text
children.value: Of course, the Pyrphorians have been waiting. The warehouse appears to be workshop for the production of devotional sculptures, its tables now flipped into barricades. Bullets ting through the many hundred stone representations of the goddess Pyr, as bodies drop on both sides. Eventually, the cultists prove too few. Having honoured the dead, you conduct a search. There is no contract, but a fiery oculus stares up from the floor, it is a Pyrphorian paper tract— an invitation to a rally at the Casado estate.

children.name: Text
children.value: Your feeble bunch finally edge open the heavy door, only to find the building deserted. That it is owned by the Pyrphorians there is no doubt. Carmine drapes smother the windows, and your people find themselves picking over the cult's instruments, whose purpose is unsettlingly opaque. "What's this oily liquid on the floor," someone says, just as the door slams shut, and is followed by the hasty rattle of padlock and keys. The Pyrphorian fire will burn bright and long at the quayside this night. Only one of your crew return home.

children.name: Text
children.value: Find some way to sneak inside

children.name: Text
children.value: Your crew stalk noiselessly around the back. Scaling the wall they find an open window obscured by a heavy carmine drape. Peering beyond it, they see a workshop for the production of devotional sculptures, its tables now flipped into barricades. With the cultists' attentions fixed on the main door, you are able to ambush them before it turns into a gunfight, but that doesn't stop two of your own being shot dead. Having honoured the dead, your survivors conduct a search. There is no contract, but a fiery oculus stares up from the floor, it is a Pyrphorian paper tract— an invitation to a rally at the Casado estate.

children.name: Text
children.value: They thought they had been quiet as church mice, but rounding the corner at the back of the warehouse, they have a nasty shock. Upon the balcony above, where you might have thought to gain entry to the warehouse, stands a single Pyrphorian clad in heavy garb, in his hands a long brass pipe from the aperture of which erupts a searing cone of fire. Your people spread and dive for the sea, and the Pyrphorians torch your ship. Only one of your crew return home.

children.name: Text
children.value: Fan through the city, looking for clues.

children.name: Text
children.value: Your scouts pick up the scent immediately. "We recognised them as the fugitives from the boat we pursued, and followed them through Montoya to its outskirts. Up in the valley there is a sizeable house on a large estate. They must have taken the contract there." You set off at once.

children.name: Text
children.value: It seems the Pyrphorians have split. One you trace as far as the church, the other to a house of ill-repute— alternate refuges of the typical criminal. In neither case are the Pyrphorians still in evidence - you will have to ask one of the respective proprietors.

children.name: Text
children.value: Go to the church and ask the Priest for help

children.name: Text
children.value: None better than the priest, hidden in shadow, witness to every confession, to guide you. "Yes, the rogues were here, but they are gone now, I am powerless to stop them, like everyone else." He tells how darkness grips the Montoyan community, and their suffering pours always through his doors— a last refuge for the holy. "Many speak of a ranch, the one a little way up the valley, and a beacon, some infernal eye, that holds their wicked congregation rapt," he says. You realise if that contract is anywhere, it is probably there.

children.name: Text
children.value: Your crew must trust themselves to the man of god. After all, he seems devoted to helping you cleanse Montoya of heresy. "No, I have not seen them," he begins, "but many of my flock have lately confessed their fears— their lost faith." He smiles blithely, and leads you from the church to a decrepit warehouse on the dock. "If you too wish to rid yourself of your demons, I encourage yout to begin here." Now forgive me, for I cannot abide violence," he says, taking his leave. You can try to break the warehouse door, or you can sneak around the back.

children.name: Text
children.value: Go to the den of ill-repute and ask the Madam for help

children.name: Text
children.value: The Madam is only too happy to help following such charming propitiations. "Yes, the devils were here. They always are." She leads you through a lanterned garden of red dahlia, and points you up the valley to a ranch. "The sort of eye you seek is up there, at the casona," she clutches her wrist suddenly, "searing, burning— The oculus." Lifting her hand she reveals a grotesque brand on her skin. Mildly troubled, you set out for the ranch.

children.name: Text
children.value: The Madam refuses to help without payment. Time is money, and your mumbling mummers are wasting it.

children.name: Text
children.value: Spend some time in the establishment

children.name: Text
children.value: All are commendably well-behaved. Your sailors make surprisingly good companions, all paying what they owe. "Now that I have some evidence as to your good character," says the Madam, "I will help you." She leads you through a lanterned garden of red dahlia, and points you up the valley to a ranch. "The sort of eye you seek is up there, at the casona," she clutches her wrist suddenly, "searing, burning— The oculus." Lifting her hand she reveals a grotesque brand on her skin. Thanking her for her hospitality, you set out for the ranch.

children.name: Text
children.value: After an hour your sailors are all over the place, singing and carousing, one refusing to pay for services rendered. "Get them out!" screams the Madam. "But what of the information you promised?", "Out!". You have created enough of a scene. Fortunately two boys waiting outside cheerily agree to help you for a bit of coin. They lead your band to a warehouse from they claim eerie sounds emanate at night, in their words, like "stakes being driven through the hearts of vampyrs." The door to the warehouse looks breakable.

children.name: Text
children.value: "Alright, Alright," she says bitterly, "Yes, the devils were here. They always are." She leads you through a lanterned garden of red dahlia, and points you up the valley to a ranch. "The sort of eye you seek is up there, at the casona," she clutches her wrist suddenly, "searing, burning... the oculus." Lifting her hand she reveals a brand on her skin. Feeling vaguely guilty for adding to the poor woman's woes, you set out for the ranch.

children.name: Text
children.value: She becomes strangely compliant, as if she is used to empty aggression. "This way," she says with forced sensuality. She takes you backwards over your own steps to the dock, and gestures a silked sleeve (from which no hand protrudes) to a decrepit-looking warehouse. "There. I must leave you now." The warehouse door looks breakable.

children.name: Text
children.value: There is no sign of the Pyrphorians, at least not that any of your twits see. Giving up their search, they begin stopping locals in the street. Most shake them off and walk on in a hurry. But they finally seem to strike lucky when two boys cheerily agree to help for a bit of coin. They lead your band to a warehouse from which they claim eerie sounds emanate at night, in their words, like "stakes being driven through the hearts of vampyrs." The door to the warehouse looks breakable.

children.name: Text
children.value: The Prosperity contract must be here. The Casona looks quite modern, with its white walls and pleasant gables. There is even an adjoining orangery, that extends naturally towards the neat parterres of a sweet-smelling garden. An arc of white gravel serves as a drive, and long lines of equally white picket border the acreage in typically colonial style. Indeed were it not for the unusual height of this perimeter, and the shelters abutting it at intervals— armed guards no doubt stationed in each— it would appear much as any other estate. You consider your plan of entry.

children.name: Text
children.value: Play it bold, launching an assault on the house

children.name: Text
children.value: The guards at the main gate are efficiently dispatched, and their keys are taken. Your brigade flood into the ranch in formation, taking cover behind hedge and shrubbery, as the scattered enemy attempts to muster. Sure enough the robes begin to flow, and the petit pistols are out.

children.name: Text
children.value:
The Pyrphorian defence is short-lived, and your lose no-one. Leaving the dying Pyrphorians to bask in last light, you enter the house by the front door.
Your party meet with no resistance in the vestibule, only dread. It is a large open room, with stairs at either side. A series of Pre-Raphaelite panels depicting Pyr the fire mother adorn the walls. In one, she stands beneath a dark and cosmic sky, disciples at her feet, each holding a braid of her flaming hair. The most striking feature of the room however, is the dome in the centre, which from below appears at first convex, and is painted in every detail as a human eye. The Oculus. A pinprick of sunlight falls from its pupil to an ominous platform, thick with ash. You cannot find that contract soon enough.

children.name: Text
children.value:
Marathon battle style. It works, the guards are defeated. A few sailors are injured but now the road to the house is open.
Inside the house, which room to look for?

Your strategy is too clever for your forces, who despite outnumbering the Pyrphorians three-to-one, are marginal victors. With a war at stake, you must hurry on to the house.

children.name: Text
children.value: Discouraged, the crew is forced to return to Isabel's island. "We lost them" apologises the captain. But a few days later, Isabel receives a letter from one of her scouting parties, 'Pyrphorian vessel spotted entering Montoya harbour." With renewed hope, the crew prepares to leave at once. The contract and those Pyrphorians must be here in Montoya, but where? The city sprawls before you under a pastel blue sky, the distinctive whitewall and terracotta of Imperial La Corona glowing softly all along the narrow estuary where the Mixcoatl meets the ocean. Yet, tranquil it is not. Anxiety is written in every passing face. They must know who you are and what you seek, but finding one brave enough to share is a different matter. You can ask around, or rely instead on your own eyes to find clues.

children.name: Text
children.value: The sole survivor succeeds in getting back to Isabel's island. In his panic, he explains that the rest didn't make it, and describes how he traced the enemy back to an estate outside Montoya. A crew is assembled at once. They arrive to find the Casona looks quite modern, with its white walls and pleasant gables. The Prosperity contract must be here. An adjoining orangery extends naturally towards the neat parterres of a sweet-smelling garden. An arc of white gravel serves as a drive, and long lines of equally white picket border the acreage in typical colonial style. Indeed were it not for the unusual height of this perimeter, and the shelters abutting it at intervals— armed guards no doubt stationed in each— it would appear much as any other estate. You consider your plan of entry.

children.name: Text
children.value: You finally have your hands on the Prosperity contract! Now there's a chance of clearing your father's name, and by so doing, preventing the outbreak of war between Isabel Sarmento and the Queen.

children.name: Text
children.value: It is no coincidence that the trail of roses in Her Majesty's wake has ended in this pretty continental town. What can have caused her to cross a narrow sea, poppy-flecked fields, and mythical river valleys? She has not simply waltzed over for the ambience— this is the heartland of her maternal family line, and she is here with a purpose.

children.name: Text
children.value: She's a Queen, there must be some sign of her somewhere...

children.name: Text
children.value: A nearby castle or country residence, of course! "Eliminate all other factors, and what remains is the truth," as the sleuths say, and the Queen would never be content to stay in town. Calculating you are no more than two days behind the Queen's retinue, you are able to draw a circle on a map around suitably regal stopovers. It is now but a question of exactly which of her landed relatives she came here to visit...

children.name: Text
children.value: Use your knowledge of the royal family to make a guess

children.name: Text
children.value: Your familiarity with the Teutonic dynasties stands you in good stead. Whispers at home are growing ever louder on the subject the Queen's suitors, and her cousin Ernest seems to be one of the front-runners. You visit the outspoken prince consort at his ivy-clad burg, and having presented a letter Sir Archibald gave you, he nods and leads you through its low, rib-vaulted ceilings, past gilt-candelabras and canvas portraits. Though cordial, Prince Ernest seems a little twitchy.

children.name: Text
children.value: You know it's the wrong choice from the moment you walk into the parlour. The Duchess, who is of middle-age, lies half-asleep in a four-posted bed, which from her dishevilled appearance it seems she has not left in days. "Excuse my zurprise," she croaks, "But a Queen, come here? When our zide of the family has been neglected for years?" She feigns a tortured expression. "But now we have darling visitors!" Anxious not to offend, you remain in her company until she eventually tires of her games. She lets slip the Queen is visiting her cousin, Prince Ernest. The Prince offers you a cordial welcome at his ivy-clad castle, but appears twitchy throughout.

children.name: Text
children.value: Try to read his thoughts through his twitches

children.name: Text
children.value: "From your movements, I sense that you too are worried for her welfare." The subtlety of your deduction surprises Prince Ernest. He nods silently, and falls heavily into the ornate chair behind his desk. "She asked me to help trace our shared lineage— to establish the validity of certain claims she has through her ancestral ties to La Corona." Ernest pauses and crunches nervously on some recently-acquired shortbread. "She had wanted to do it alone for once. But she risks herself, and I have now decided you must go after her— There is to be a masked ball in Monégasque. You will find her there.

children.name: Text
children.value: Your strange deduction offends Prince Ernest. "From your movements, I sense this is a matter of the heart," is what you had said. Prince Ernest had then turned his back on you gothically, shouting — "How dare you; prying into her personal affairs, as they all did during the crushing confines of her youth!" — before storming into the gardens to sulk. The next day the Prince seems only very slightly calmer, "she asked me to help trace our family tree— that is all. I will not stop you going after her, in spite of your impertinence, only because I am concerned for her welfare. There is to be a masked ball in Monégasque. You will find her there."

children.name: Text
children.value: You can't imagine where she could have stayed in this town, pretty as it may be. You leave and take the road south, stopping beside an orchard to rest. Your knowledge of local dialect is passable enough to overhear fruit-pickers talking about a recent and distinguished visitor. Curious, you ask them if they are referring to your Queen, at which they fall silent. It seems they must have sworn to secrecy.

children.name: Text
children.value: Gently encourage them to give up all they know

children.name: Text
children.value: Your authoritative presence unsettles them into confessing all they know, which frankly, being fruit-pickers, isn't much more than you. Although one thing they have heard is that the Queen will be staying in luxury with family — a country residence, or castle with pointy tourelles, no doubt. It is now but a question of exactly which of her landed relatives she came here to visit...

children.name: Text
children.value: The fruit-pickers don't believe you are who you threaten to be, and if anything, your surly attitude makes them wonder if it could be you the Queen is running away from. They call out to the rest of the pickers, who stand shoulder-to-shoulder with them in case you should think of taking things any further. Turning miserably back to your carriage in the road, it is only after considerable soul-searching that you re-read Sir Archibald's briefing, "despite her secrecy, a Queen never travels humbly." Of course, how stupid! One of the countless castles that dominate the hills all around. It is now but a question of exactly which of her landed relatives she came here to visit...

children.name: Text
children.value: Offer them a suitably regal incentive for the information

children.name: Text
children.value: If you want to bribe us, it had better be all the wonderz of the high life!

children.name: Text
children.value: They accept your offer, "she stay with family— at ze castle!" You are astonished to learn that the Queen dragged her skirts through the mud of the orchard, insisting that all her finely-dressed footmen should be fed and watered, and that no-one should know she or her retinue were there. One of the pickers you bribed laughs, emulating her speech, "I hope you don't zink me too bohemian a Monarch." His friend reminds him with a sharp nudge that mocking the Queen might not be the best idea. It is now just a question of exactly which of her landed relatives she came here to visit...

children.name: Text
children.value: They refuse. Clearly the fear of divine retribution against those who defy royalty is too strong. They call out to the rest of the pickers, who stand shoulder-to-shoulder with them in case you should want to take things any further. You turn miserably back to the carriage in the road, and it is only after hours of hopeful meandering in this beautiful country that you recall Sir Archibald's briefing, "despite her secrecy, a Queen never travels humbly." Of course, how stupid! One of the countless castles that dominate the hills all around. It is just a question of exactly which of her landed relatives she came here to visit...

children.name: Text
children.value: Ask a respectable-looking local if they've seen a fugitive Queen...

children.name: Text
children.value: They don't take much convincing to tell you what they know, especially when you seem so sympathetic to the challenges of peasant life; "Passing foreign Queens expect your silence for nothing, and yet it is you who must die in the fields for your masters when the harvest has failed." They grumble in recognition, noting that the Queen thought the town beneath her, and went off to stay in a nearby castle. It is now just a question of exactly which of her landed relatives she came here to visit...

children.name: Text
children.value: The locals are stubborn in their silence. The Queen is a relative of those who own the land they work, and they fear for their livelihoods. There are further confirmations that the Queen passed through however, which lead you to the unlikely environs of a cider orchard. Two likely-looking pickers stand at the gate, both unable to disguise that they have recently met royalty, or that they have promised to say nothing to that matter.

children.name: Text
children.value: Use deduction to discern which royal the Queen is visiting

children.name: Text
children.value: You sneak upon proof it is her cousin Ernest she was visiting. While the Prince's welcome is polite, his stiffness of manner alerts your suspicions. And when, after tea, he gives you the freedom of the ivy-clad castle, you waste no time seeking signs she was there. You find paper on the desk in a guest bedroom impressed with quill-marks, and make a rubbing. A letter from the queen to her handmaid! It largely concerns itself with Ernest's handsome looks.When you rasie the subject with Prince Ernest, he becomes rather twitchy.

children.name: Text
children.value: You are led a merry dance. It transpires the Queen has made several visits to family in the region, staying very briefly at each estate before being driven on to the next with her modest retinue. You try to puzzle the ultimate purpose of this, but can deduce nothing, and must go around the houses before you arrive exhausted at the ivy-clad castle of Consort Prince Ernest. His nervous disposition suggests he knows the Queen's intentions in visiting.

children.name: Text
children.value: Tell him that your only wish is to help the Queen

children.name: Text
children.value: "Very well," agrees the Prince, once your persuasive speech has come to an end, "My dear cousin asked me to help trace our shared lineage— to establish the validity of certain claims she has through ancestral ties to La Corona." He removes a map of the continent from his neatly-arranged bureau. "Your diplomatic immunity may prove important in the days ahead. What she plans may put her at risk." He sighs. "There is to be a masked ball in Monégasque. You will find her there."

children.name: Text
children.value: You have lost some face in royal circles. "I shall tell you nothing, nothing!" Prince Ernest says curtly, exhausted by your chatter, "yet another prying into her personal affairs, as so many did through the crushing confines of her youth!" The Queen's cousin then storms into the gardens to sulk. The next day he seems only very slightly calmer, "she asked me to help trace our family tree— that is all. I will not stop you going after her, in spite of your impertinence, only because I am concerned for her welfare. There is to be a masked ball in Monégasque. You will find her there."

children.name: Text
children.value: Following Prince Ernest's advice, you travel by train along the sparkling Côte Turquoise to a grand station in the sophisticated principality of Monégasque. Ruled for six centuries by the Piedmont family, today the streets of Monégasque are filled with colour and light, for it is the grand opening of its very first casino! The theme is animal masquerade, and you see disturbing furred and feathered costumes at every turn. Convenient for a Queen going incognito... Prince Ernest gave you his own invitation to the casino, but you will also need a costume.

children.name: Text
children.value: Splash out on a fancy costume

children.name: Text
children.value: The costumier waits, hands on hips, her face pale and smooth with crème céleste.

children.name: Text
children.value: You can't help but feel you paid rather a lot for the last-minute tailoring, which in fairness the costumier hammers out with astonishing calm. You get changed and observe the result in the long mirror — what you see is reminiscent of Alice's cheshire cat, or better, that pussy cat famously employed to fetch royal mice. You meow past the casino doormen, and once inside, debate your best bet for finding the Queen.

children.name: Text
children.value: The costumier turns up her lips in disgust. It seems you can't afford to pay the going rate for a last-minute costume, so you'll have to meet the casino dress code in some other way.

children.name: Text
children.value: Try to mingle in high society

children.name: Text
children.value: Your knowledge of royalty does not desert you; in a circle of the most elegantly-dressed people, you spy a beautiful sequined elephant, in whose hand is a foul mixture of claret and malt whisky— the Queen's favourite. Your eyes meet, and hers widen. She drops her glass, and there are gasps as she rushes for the exit. By the time you have forced your way outside, her carriage has set off at speed. You wave another cab down, and get in.

children.name: Text
children.value: You can't tell anyone here apart, as far as you are concerned, they might as well all be princes, queens and kings! Suddenly a silence falls, and the Prince of Monégasque himself— a man with an improbably thin moustache, makes a long speech about how the casino will bring back the good times for the Piedmont family. "And finally, I notice we have a special guest," he smiles, at which a sequined elephant promptly rushes for the door, "but, oh your majesty, wait!!" But by the time you have forced your way outside, her carriage has set off at speed. You wave another cab down, and get in.

children.name: Text
children.value: See if you can find her at the gaming tables

children.name: Text
children.value: Your luck does not desert you, and soon among those drawn to your blessed table, you spy a beautiful sequined elephant. Your eyes meet, and hers widen. She must recognise you! There are gasps as she rushes for the exit. By the time you have forced your way outside, her carriage has set off at speed. You wave another cab down, and get in.

children.name: Text
children.value: Your luck is dreadful, and you are so preoccupied with the roulette wheel, you fail to notice that your Queen is indeed present. Suddenly a silence falls, and the Prince of Monégasque himself— a man with an improbably thin moustache, makes a long speech about how the casino will bring back the good times for the Piedmont family. "And finally, I notice we have a special guest," he smiles, at which a sequined elephant promptly rushes for the door, "but, oh your majesty, wait!!" But by the time you have forced your way outside, her carriage has set off at speed. You wave another cab down, and get in.

children.name: Text
children.value: Make a costume of your own

children.name: Text
children.value: Cunning and resourceful, you acquire and combine every accoutrement needed to give you the appearance of a fox. Twirling your catgut whiskers, and dashing up the marble steps, you brush slyly past the casino doormen, and once inside, debate your best bet for finding the Queen.

children.name: Text
children.value: A shambolic cow costume! You could barely have come up with anything less voguish. The doormen are too serious to laugh, and instead escort you to one side, "this is a society event! It doesn't matter who you are, you can't come in dressed like that!" If you are going to get in and find the Queen, you'll have to settle for a less fashionable route.

children.name: Text
children.value: Shamelessly walk in without a costume

children.name: Text
children.value: A few heads turn, but the doormen don't stop you. "I'm a special guest of the Piedmont family," you say with a winning smile, as you brandish the invitation Prince Ernest gave you, "expected to donate great sums to the cause. So you can forgive my choice of attire." One of the doormen hands you a black eye mask, which you put on, reserved no doubt for exceptional circumstances such as this. Once inside the casino, you debate your best bet for finding the Queen.

children.name: Text
children.value: It seems they will make no exceptions. "This is a society event," says the doorman in exasperation, "it doesn't matter who you are, you can't come in dressed like that!" If you are going to get in and find the Queen, you'll have to settle for a less fashionable route.

children.name: Text
children.value: You show off your powers of mystery. As you stalk around to the promenade behind the casino, you are hit by a warm riviera breeze and the sight of exotic palms. There is a bathroom window open up above. The stucco holds as you shimmy up unseen, swinging your legs over the threshold. Finally inside the casino, you debate your best bet for finding the Queen.

children.name: Text
children.value: Not as stealthy as you had imagined. As you stalk around to the promenade behind the casino, you are hit by a warm riviera breeze and the sight of exotic palms. You scale the wall without incident, but then accidently trip through a skylight. You crunch onto the rug of a guest bedroom in a rain of shattered crystal. Luckily the guest is downstairs playing craps and will not discover this mess until much later. Trying to summon whatever remaining grace you have, you make your way inside the casino and debate your best bet for finding the Queen.

children.name: Text
children.value: Go round the back and force your way in

children.name: Text
children.value: You show your strength. As you stalk around to the promenade behind the casino, you are hit by a warm riviera breeze and the sight of exotic palms. The doorman on this side looks feeble. You walk up to him and pop him on the nose, take his plain black eye mask for yourself, and saunter into the casino. Once inside, you debate your best bet for finding the Queen.

children.name: Text
children.value: Unfortunately, it's a pretty even contest. As you stalk around to the promenade behind the casino, you are hit by a warm riviera breeze and the sight of exotic palms. The doorman on this side looks muscular, at least compared to you. You take a swing at him, catching him by surprise, but he comes back hard, and a scuffle develops. "I yield," he says finally. Dusting yourself off, you take his plain black eye mask to cover your black eyes and bloody nose, and shamble into the casino. Once inside, you debate your best bet for finding the Queen.

children.name: Text
children.value: Offer the doormen a donation towards the casino

children.name: Text
children.value: "Oh, so you wish to make a significant donation to the Piedmont family?" said the doorman with a smirk.

children.name: Text
children.value: "Very well," agrees the doorman, "the Prince of Monégasque kindly accepts your donation, and wishes you should have a fine evening at his casino." Once inside, you debate your best bet for finding the Queen.

children.name: Text
children.value: "No, no," one of the doormen shakes his head, "the Prince of Monégasque would not accept such a donation. I am under strict instructions only to admit those in suitable costume." It seems you'll have to settle for a less fashionable route.

children.name: Text
children.value: The Queen fled the casino at speed, and your own carriage is some distance behind. Your driver thinks she is headed up the coast, perhaps to a ship. You can either keep up your pursuit, or else rush to your own ship, which, if the orders you gave to the captain have been followed, should be waiting in the Monégasque marina.

children.name: Text
children.value: You reach the next bay up from Monégasque, and hopping out of your carriage, see the Queen bustling along a jetty at which a great flagship dubbed "Lap of Victory" is moored. Obviously she has primed them for such an emergency, as they all seem ready to go. You can try to call out to the Queen, or else borrow a vessel to continue your pursuit.

children.name: Text
children.value: You comport yourself with dignity, "Your Majesty, please, I'm not here to seize you, but to assist you in any way I am able!" The short rotund figure turns, dresses in hand, and a small but shrill voice floats back towards you over the sound of the sea. "Meet me at the Cape of Trelawney!" You find your own ship at the marina, and sail to Trelawney, southernmost point of the Old World. It was not fifteen years previous, that a great naval victory was won here over La Corona by one Admiral Nadasky. The Lap of Victory is there waiting for you, and the Queen receives you warmly aboard. You are finally able to ask her why it is she has run away.

children.name: Text
children.value: You cannot keep the irritation from your voice, "Your Majesty, please, desist from this charade!" The short rotund figure turns, dresses in hand, and a small but defiant voice floats cuts the sound of the sea. "I am not a child, I am your Queen! Be at the Cape of Trelawney tomorrow, or else." You slink off to find your ship at the marina and head for Trelawney, southernmost point of the Old World, where not fifteen years previous, a great naval victory was won over La Corona by the heroic Admiral Nadasky. The Lap of Victory is there waiting for you, and the Queen receives you rather icily aboard. With a gulp, you are finally able to ask why it is she has run away.

children.name: Text
children.value: "Your helmsmanship is most impressive!" the Queen calls down to you, as you bring the modest sailing ship you have borrowed neatly alongside her flagship."Meet me tomorrow at the Cape of Trelawney!" You find your own ship at the marina, and sail to Trelawney, southernmost point of the Old World. It was not fifteen years previous, that a great naval victory was won here over La Corona by one Admiral Nadasky.The Lap of Victory is there waiting for you, and the Queen receives you warmly aboard. You are finally able to ask why it is she has run away.

children.name: Text
children.value: "A limp effort!" the Queen bellows down to you, as you bring the leaky fishing boat you have stolen alongside her gigantic flagship. Rather than leave you to flounder, she seems to have taken pity on you and slowed down."Meet me at the Cape of Trelawney, and good heavens, bring a proper vessel!" You slink off to find your ship at the marina and head for Trelawney, southernmost point of the Old World, where not fifteen years previous, a great naval victory was won over La Corona by the heroic Admiral Nadasky. The Lap of Victory is there waiting for you, and the Queen receives you rather icily aboard. With a gulp, you are finally able to ask why it is she has run away.

children.name: Text
children.value: Your ship is indeed waiting in the marina. Quickly, you rouse the captain and his crew, and weigh anchor. Before long, twinkling Monégasque is behind you, and from the next bay, you spot an impressive ship in the distance. How was she able to leave port so fast? You either can continue to chase Her Majesty, or send her a message of peace with your signal lamp.

children.name: Text
children.value: "Your helmsmanship is most impressive!" the Queen calls over to you, as you bring your ship up alongside hers."Meet me at the Cape of Trelawney!"You point your ship towards Trelawney, southernmost point of the Old World, where not fifteen years previous, a great naval victory was won over La Corona by the heroic Admiral Nadasky.The Lap of Victory is there waiting for you, and the Queen receives you warmly aboard. You are finally able to ask why it is she has run away.

children.name: Text
children.value: "A limp effort!" the Queen bellows over to you, as you struggle to bring your ship alongside the gigantic flagship. You would never have caught her had she not taken pity on you and slowed down."You'd better meet me at the Cape of Trelawney, if indeed, you are capable!" Slightly hurt, you point your ship towards Trelawney, southernmost point of the Old World, where not fifteen years previous, a great naval victory was won over La Corona by the heroic Admiral Nadasky. The Lap of Victory is there waiting for you, and the Queen receives you rather icily aboard. With a gulp, you are finally able to ask why it is she has run away.

children.name: Text
children.value: The Queen takes the time to answer. You flashed "ONLY DESIRE TO HELP MAJESTY," with the Columb light, and received "FOLLOW US!" in reply. You are travelling towards Trelawney, southernmost point of the Old World, where not fifteen years previous, a great naval victory was won over La Corona by the heroic Admiral Nadasky. The Lap of Victory is there waiting for you, and the Queen receives you warmly aboard. You are finally able to ask why it is she has run away.

children.name: Text
children.value: You receive no answer. Looking at your message again, it does seem a little abrupt— "STOP IN THE NAME OF SIR ARCHIBALD." You pursue at great distance towards Trelawney, southernmost point of the Old World, where not fifteen years previous, a great naval victory was won over La Corona by the heroic Admiral Nadasky. The Lap of Victory slows to a halt, and the Queen receives you rather icily aboard. With a gulp, you are finally able to ask why it is she has run away.

children.name: Text
children.value: The first severe blizzard. You have just caught sight of the Baffling Island littoral, when the headwind suddenly whips up and a dark fringe of cloud appears in the heavens. All take cover below deck, as rock-hard pellets of ice begin to pelt the ship with such force as to cause lasting damage. "We've lost control of her," screams the navigator, but it'd take a hero to go back out into that.

children.name: Text
children.value: Send your best to put away the sails

children.name: Text
children.value: Worthy heroes step forward. "Whatever this ship and her crew needs," says the burliest, before striding out into the storm. Undeterred by the snow and buffeting of the wind, they put the sails 'in their gear'— loosing the sheetlines, and pulling the buntlines through, until the ship is running under jib alone. The storm passes, and the crew feel invincible.

children.name: Text
children.value: Not easy handling sails at minus thirty, and while those brave enough to take on the ice storm are strong enough, their labour is clumsy. As the snowblasted sails are loosened, your men allow them to catch a crosswind and suddenly they are off! Flapping wildly against a creaking mainmast, the sails are threatening to rip half the ship away.

children.name: Text
children.value: Twang! The sails flap away into dark drifts of snow. Your able-footed sailor reaching every rope without slip, and the snowflakes crowding his eyes unable to prevent the skillful execution of his art. Next day the Arctic sky is still once more. "The mast is intact, and we've spare rope and sail," says the carpenter, "we'll be all right."

children.name: Text
children.value: Your men cannot keep their footing for the ice on deck, and the hard rocking of the ship gives them further excuse to lower their swords. They can only watch as, under the pull of the sails, the mainmast cracks open like grissini, the upper section cartwheeling out to sea, a tangle of rigging behind it. The crew are all accounted-for, but the damage to the ship is probably irreparable.

children.name: Text
children.value: Cut the ropes holding the sails

children.name: Text
children.value: Let the blizzard do its worst

children.name: Text
children.value: The mainmast takes much of the brunt, whipped and contorted in every direction by the impassioned sails. When the storm and seizures finally end, the carpenter tallies the cost of your inaction. "There's fissures in the mast. It may hold with enough resin, then again, maybe not..."

children.name: Text
children.value: A bunch of wet lettuces. They claim that the rigging is too slippery to grip. If these are your best sailors, lord help the others, but those sails must come down— the ship is being blown towards some jagged silhouette! You can grab something to aid the climb or get them up there quick.

children.name: Text
children.value: At least no-one dies. The crew raid stores for ropes and chains so as to climb the rigging safely, before stowing the sails away. The ship slows but does not completely halt, colliding with that silhouette — a small and craggy island — and damaging the hull. The crew have some lengthy repairs ahead of them.

children.name: Text
children.value: A disaster of their own fashioning. Instead of finding a proper solution, the crew hurriedly don standard-issue gloves. The leather is so smooth in the palm, it is worse than climbing with no gloves at all. The ship lurches inexorably into that silhouette— a hideously craggy isle — and the impact flings the gripless riggers into the water. Visibility is so poor, and the water so cold, that there's no hope of saving those gone overboard.

children.name: Text
children.value: Order the cowards up that mast quick!

children.name: Text
children.value: Filled with doubt, they do as instructed. The conditions are dreadful, and they can barely see to work in the sideways slather and what with the waves buffeting the ship. A man falls from the upper rigging, and is found to be only loosely intact. "What are you trying to prove?!" bellows the navigator above the whine of the wind. Finally, the sails are put up and the boat can ride out the remainder of the storm without blowing off course. Your crew are incensed at the coldness of their superiors.

children.name: Text
children.value: Faith and prudence. Your sailors huddle below, rocked hard, but out of harm's way. They resist the temptation to attend the creaking ship and its rudder and trust their course to the divine. Soon the grog is flowing, sailors play at cribbage, and all forget where they be. "Hold! I hear no storm," a sailor says suddenly. The hatch is opened to reveal stillness and stars, and a harlequin snake of an aurora, smiling down benevolent.

children.name: Text
children.value: Your sailors will not wait for god. The storm shrieks its name, as sailors muttered frenzied supplications to the nameless. "To hell and damn you all, I want to die living," the others bellow at them, and so unchained, they rush out into the white. Harsh commands can be heard above, before those voices fall silent. Somehow the ship rides out the storm, but the bodies of your saviours are never found.

children.name: Text
children.value: Protect the steamship any way you can

children.name: Text
children.value: You have a hardy legion indeed. They rush to the tarpaulins, and with commendable teamwork and physical strength in the challenging conditions, are able to pull them over the ship's most sensitive instruments and machinery. Heading below deck to relax, the heroes wait out the storm in luxury with buttered currant buns and hot tea.

children.name: Text
children.value: Their defence of the ship is a little half-hearted. Initially the men show willing, but the blizzard quickly wears them down, and they retreat inside claiming that their work is done. After the worst of it has passed, the officers survey the ship. Beneath a poorly affixed and feeble tarpaulin, the engine is found flooded with slush that must now be cleared. One has to wonder if they are cut out for these kinds of challenges.

children.name: Text
children.value: Tragic youthful over-exuberance. Your sailors drain a bottle of strong rum before going back out, perhaps believing machismo will keep them warm. They batten the hatches in the white flurry, stumbling, belching and laughing. The hilarity continues when one of the lads slips and loses his feet, that is until the steel rim of the funnel meets his head with a clomp. He dies instantly.

children.name: Text
children.value: Send an expert diver to unclog the propellers of ice

children.name: Text
children.value: The thrill-seeking diver relishes the task. Covering themselves in bear fat and brandishing a sharp pick, they enter the water without a splash, resurfacing no more than five minutes later to the embrace of a pre-warmed towel. "All clear!" your diver says. Cheers go up below at the sound of the engines at full power once more.

children.name: Text
children.value: Resume the expedition under clearer skies...

children.name: Text
children.value: "Sir!" cries the lookout, "dark shapes on the ridge!" A group climb the icy escarpment. At the top they find a companionable trio of driftwood boards plugged in three man-sized heaps of snow. Sunlight hits the scritchings in the wood, "Sacred to the memory of Joseph Braine, who departed this life New Year's Day 1846 on board of H.M. Styx." The others named are "John Gore" and "Francis Seeley." Your men tremble at the idea of disturbing the graves.

children.name: Text
children.value: Dig up the graves no matter the crew's fears

children.name: Text
children.value:
The crew agree to draw lots. A scrawny man gets the shovel, and clears snow to reveal Braine's face, who might look asleep but for his skin of leather. In his pocket, a letter to his wife.
Dearest Elaine,
I've few breaths left. I die never having found a Passage, but then no glory awaits any servant of Sir John. He was certain the ice would not thicken around us in Spring. Fate of expedition now rests on circumnavigation of Labrador Island by short, perilous west shore, or by long, open east channel— fear I know what Sir John will prefer.
Farewell my Elaine.

children.name: Text
children.value:
A hundred metres from the graves, the men find the remains of a camp at which the lost expedition wintered. They built a cairn— a stack of stones— under which a tin cylinder containing a tightly-rolled letter is found. "They left a note of their progress," the captain says. Lady Faithful recognizes her husband's handwriting.
May 28th, 1847 { H.M. ships 'Styx' and 'Hades' wintered in the ice in lat. 70˚ 05' N ; long. 98˚ 23' W. Having wintered in 1846-7 at Baffling Island, in lat. 74˚ 43' 28" N., long. 91˚ 39' 15" W., after having sailed Wailing Channel to lat. 77˚, and returned by the west side of Cornell Island. Total loss by deaths to this date has been 3 men due to sickness — Braine, Gore and Seeley, God rest their souls. Leaving tomorrow for Labrador Island. Aim to reach Passage by end June; we must be close now. John Faithful, Commander, HMS Styx.

children.name: Text
children.value: Circle the island along the west coast

children.name: Text
children.value: Circle the island along the east coast

children.name: Text
children.value: The ship is now headed for the West coast of Labrador Island. The crew hope to find Sir John and his men soon, and they pray no more obstacles will come their way.

children.name: Text
children.value: The ship is now headed for the East coast of Labrador Island. The crew hope to find Sir John and his men soon, and they pray no more obstacles will come their way.

children.name: Text
children.value: Over The Ice To Huddlesome Bay

children.name: Text
children.value: As you near the coast, a large human construction delineates itself, "Most probably an abandoned trading post of the Huddlesome Bay company." It leans hard into the wind, its once-red boards scoured pale. If Sir John and his crew came this way, they would likely have stopped here. "What of getting there, sir?" says the ship's boy. He has noticed that an ice sheet lies between your ship and the trading post.

children.name: Text
children.value: Take the safest route by avoiding cracks

children.name: Text
children.value: Your crew's instincts are solid. Keeping a distance apart, they move at a purposeful speed, avoiding cracks and the dark splodges indicative of thinner ice. They reach the abandoned building without incident.

children.name: Text
children.value: Knowledge is shaky. One of your groups avoids the gaping holes, but fails to notice darker patches of thin ice. Cracking can be heard, but none of the group dare move. They hit the water with a woosh as the brûlée snaps. It is freezing, and they are struggling to climb out alone. If not rescued quickly they'll die of hypothermia.

children.name: Text
children.value: Haul the sailors out with a rope

children.name: Text
children.value: The rope team keep balance. Lying down, and spreading out to distribute the weight, they throw ropes to those in the water, who thrash to bind themselves under the armpits. On a count of three, they are hoisted clear of the water. Wet and chattering with cold, your expedition takes refuge in the old trading post.

children.name: Text
children.value: Forget strength, what they needed was teamwork. The rope team disregard their own safety and pull as they would on dry land. The ice can't hold, and collapses beneath them. Some manage to crawl free of the water and save themselves but others slip away to fertilise the ocean bed. The survivors trudge for the thin comforts of the disused trading post.

children.name: Text
children.value: They make it. They're okay!— cheered across the line in a spirit akin to the finish of a cross-country at school back home. Nobody left behind then, and nobody left behind now. Wet and chattering with cold, your expedition take refuge in the abandoned building, offering up prayers of gratitude.

children.name: Text
children.value: To those in the water the encouragement sounds noticeably strained. Convulsing as they slip down between part-frozen cuboids, their resolve fades with the voices, the light above ever more distant. Knowing they could have done more, the survivors trudge for the thin comforts of the disused trading post.

children.name: Text
children.value: Measure the thickness of the ice

children.name: Text
children.value: The ship's carpenters improvise with a rotary drill. It takes a fair bit of effort to get it turning, suggesting the ice is pretty solid. The first measurement is 11 inches— no hazard even for a sizeable group to pass over. Every few steps a new reading is taken, but it proves a mere formality, since the readings change very little. They make the abandoned building without incident.

children.name: Text
children.value: It was never going to work, using a heavy, blunt instrument to make his hole. Lucky as it happens, that the carpenter is alone as his sledgehammer comes down, sundering the ice all about him and casting him into the freezing water. Turns out the ice is fairly thick, but that won't save the poor fellow now. The others trudge for the thin comforts of the disused trading post in disbelief.

children.name: Text
children.value: The inevitable splosh. Despite the cold wind, it is still summer in the Arctic, and the weight of a large group of bodies would test thicker ice than this. Halfway across the sheet, there is a rasping crack, and your men are deposited in the water. In their struggle to escape they have to kick off their snow boots. Chattering, they make it to the thin comfort of the abandoned trading post with their feet in a terrible state.

children.name: Text
children.value: "At least it's a shelter," the captain remarks. The men shut the doors on the wind, to find the building interior licked with frost. Rusted hooks hang from the beams, relics of the short-lived fur trade. "Comforts are few and far between out here, I doubt Sir John would have passed it by." There must be some evidence of the lost expedition here.

children.name: Text
children.value: Search for signs of recent use

children.name: Text
children.value: No sign at all. Undisturbed in ten years or more, these cabins are just as they were when the traders left. There should be prints in the dust, objects out of place, but there aren't. Everyone concedes it is very unlikely Sir John's expedition came this way.

children.name: Text
children.value: Find information about the local area

children.name: Text
children.value: Something to go on at least. Whoever the fur traders were they left in a rush. Papers and maps are strewn about, some trodden and sodden into mush, a precious few dry and intact. Dockets are found relating to consignments received from a nearby Inuit settlement named Ivujivik, which happens also to be marked on a fragment of map. "The Inuit are sure to have noticed anyone passing through," says the Captain, "we should visit them."

children.name: Name
children.value: Go back and head west - Beechey island

children.name: Text
children.value: Go back and head west to Baffling Island

children.name: Name
children.value: Go back and head west - Add event

children.name: Text
children.value: The crew returns to the ship. Once at Tchilling Sound, they head west.

children.name: Name
children.value: Continue south toward the inuit settlement

children.name: Text
children.value: Continue south toward the Inuit settlement of Ivujivik

children.name: Name
children.value: Continue south toward the inuit settlement - Add event

children.name: Text
children.value: The crew marks the position of the Inuit settlement of Ivujivik on the map, and sets sail.

children.name: Name
children.value: Lancaster Detroit - Beechey Island or Trading Post

children.name: Text
children.value: An Arctic Welcome In Tchilling Sound

children.name: Text
children.value:
It is late summer when the expedition reaches the Tchilling Sound, and yet the conditions in these icy seas are already challenging. The wind only has to pick up, and the men are tugging up their collars and tramping below. It seems hopeless to think Sir John Faithful's men could have lasted three winters here. Beyond Tchilling Sound, the seaway divides.
To the west lie a chain of small islands separated by partially melted ice.
To the south, a long, dark headland crowned with snow, that hazes out of sight.

children.name: Text
children.value:
The route to the Inuit settlement of Ivujivik is a two day trek by foot across exposed ice flats. A small expedition party set off leaving the rest at sea to await their return.
Although the going is tough, it is not this that preoccupies the crew. As night falls, they are sure something has been following them.

children.name: Text
children.value: Stop for the night and keep watch

children.name: Text
children.value: Your sharp-eared watchman keeps vigil. In the small dark of Arctic summer, he catches the scratch of a bear's unretractable claws on ice. It is trying to approach discretely but the watchman is ready. At the sound of his gun the rest wake with a jolt, only to find a big dead bear at his feet. They celebrate their trophy, and are soon back en route to Ivujivik.

children.name: Text
children.value: A mother polar bear! Your watchman isn't used to such long days, struggling to keep his eyes open beside the hypnotic fire. A loud growl. Mother bear's claws dig deep into his spine and drags him off. Moments later, and she is back for more!

children.name: Text
children.value:
Years of ambush drills pay off. Quickly forming a circle your men level their guns into the half-light. Sensing the danger they pose, Mama bear grows more cautious, and after a single circuit of your camp, disappears out of sight.
Full of adrenaline, your scout party reach the Inuit camp.

children.name: Text
children.value: Hands trembling with fear, the men grab for their rifles, but mama bear smells their nerves and is upon them. Finally someone gets a shot away and though it misses, it scares her momentarily. Her white coat is lank with the blood of several men. Those still standing flee. The Inuit are startled when your party arrive at Ivujivik the next afternoon looking especially bedraggled.

children.name: Text
children.value: Use cunning to trick the bear

children.name: Text
children.value: Your men know they have to stand tall to face down a polar bear, and waving their coats above their heads like flags, they succeed in driving the bear away. Full of adrenaline, your scout party reach the Inuit camp.

children.name: Text
children.value: Mama bear looks angry. Your men had assumed that staring might make her back down, but she has taken it as a display of aggression. Her white coat is soon lank with the blood of several men. Those still standing flee. The Inuit are startled when your party arrive at Ivujivik the next afternoon looking especially bedraggled.

children.name: Text
children.value: Continue to walk despite being cold and exhausted

children.name: Text
children.value:
The men are strong and dedicated. They tramp through the half hour of pitch darkness normally reserved for sleep, keeping good pace. Whatever was following them has soon given up. Gazing upwards the party find themselves to be lucky observers of the aurora borealis.
They reach the Inuit settlement the following lunchtime, with a sense of wonder.

children.name: Text
children.value: One of the men struggles to keep up with his unsympathetic comrades. He is the runt, the weakest of the pack, and the polar bear knows it. The rest of the group hear a piercing scream followed by the sound of crunching and tearing. Moments later mama bear is bounding across the snow towards them, hungry for more!

children.name: Text
children.value: Ivujivik is a semi-permanent settlement. The Inuit appear worried, but nevertheless offer your men every hospitality, inviting them into a large iglu where they are served a hearty Suaasat— a meat stew— under the silent gaze of what feels like the whole village. A girl, Tapeesa, is able to translate, and the others warm up when the hear the story of your journey over the ice flats. Soon the subject turns to Sir John's lost expedition. Tapeesa shows you items that look like they belonged to Sir John's expedition.

children.name: Text
children.value: Offer to trade for the relics

children.name: Text
children.value: They were strange men. Who doesn't want to eat when they've been out in the cold...?

children.name: Text
children.value: Decline and ask how they got them.

children.name: Text
children.value: Silver cutlery embossed with the names Hades and Styx. These are from Sir John's expedition ships! There are also cufflinks belonging to Sir John engraved with assorted marsupials, and a knife handle with the emblem of the Arctic council. Tapeesa says that about a year ago, some men came wanting to know about channels through the ice, and traded their things for information. She points to the west coast of Labrador Island on your map.

children.name: Text
children.value: Ask how they got hold of them

children.name: Text
children.value: Tapeesa patiently explains that they traded with men like yours about a year ago. The men wanted to know about channels through the ice, and traded their things for information. She points to the west coast of Labrador Island on your map.

children.name: Text
children.value: Your ship is stranded on an iceberg! It is night along the east coast of Labrador Island. The meek light of your vessel seems to dissolve into the moonless blackness. Even at easy sail and under constant vigil, your ship runs the risk here, for slumbering ice giants leer from the darkness in all directions. "Dead ahead!" comes the cry, too late! A low growl shakes the boat, as a wave dumps it atop a berg— in the shape of an upturned molar— beaching it there. The ship is undamaged, if only it could be returned to the water...

children.name: Text
children.value: Nothing in nature can prevail against human endeavour, it would seem. The crew watch with trepidation as the fuses burn down to the stick, before an ear-splitting series of detonations rings across the vastness, sundering the icy claws that had held your ship hostage. A small blizzard of debris blankets the deck, to the delight of all aboard, for they are free once more!

children.name: Text
children.value: Ice crumbles all around such firepower. Any cannon that can be swiveled at the target is put to use, chipping away the ice dungeon into which the ship has become wedged until the way is clear. Then like a cheerful sea lion the fair vessel slips down an escarpment and plops back into the water. The crew cheer and continue on their way.

children.name: Text
children.value: The iceberg fights back. Though the way is almost clear, the relentless cannonfire seems to have woken the ogre below, and to the horror of the crew the vast berg rolls slightly to one side. Great shards of ice detach and bounce over the deck, injuring your men. Quick action is needed.

children.name: Text
children.value: Get out and push the ship free

children.name: Text
children.value: Your men signed up for such challenges, and scarcely need telling what to do. Leaping down from the boat, they get behind her, knotting guy ropes as only rugged sailors can. All the while the berg rumbles suggestively, but it is your committed team who prevail. Once clear of the ice field, the crew will be able to treat their wounds.

children.name: Text
children.value: It's an uphill struggle. The pitching of the unstable berg does not help a jot, as the men tumble and slide to find grip. Such is the effort required to pull the ship successfully down from the iceberg into the sea, no-one notices one of the teams is missing. It appears they have fallen through a thin part of the ice to their deaths.

children.name: Text
children.value: Let the rolling berg toss you into the sea.

children.name: Text
children.value: Your ship performs a rather messy dismount. After that intial roll, the iceberg halts long enough to suggest it wants to stay in its new position. But then everything happens all at once. The berg spins violently, and the ship with it! The ship strikes the water at such an angle that very serious damage is done to much of the lee-side. Fortunately the crew come out unharmed.

children.name: Text
children.value: Build something to help you escape

children.name: Text
children.value: The crew assembles a dozen hardy levers to free the ship. Flexible hickory planking is cut and reshaped into a wedges, before being inserted into the ice at intervals of five paces, until they surround the stern. On a count of three the men lift, and to their surprise so does the hull! Once it starts moving, there's no stopping it; and it clatters through all icy obstructions to the sea. Your sailors embrace, they have been very resourceful.

children.name: Text
children.value: The wrong wood is selected for the task. It is a decorative mahogany veneer, stripped from the captain's cabin. "Whatever it takes," the captain says with laudable magnanimity, but the whole business is futile. Despite the wedges being placed in great number at the stern of the ship, no amount of pressure from the crew can encourage the ship to move since the levers lack the requisite spring. They'll need to find another way off this berg.

children.name: Text
children.value: Search for Sir John along the east coast

children.name: Text
children.value:
Free of the Iceberg, the crew manages to circumvent Labrador Island via its easterly shore. However they have found no trace of the lost expedition. You'll have to try the west coast.
Sir John must have taken the risky option.

children.name: Text
children.value: The west coast of Labrador Island is snaggled up with monstrous horns of ice. Navigation is going to be tricky. Will the narrows lead back once more to open water, or will your ship end up stuck? You can navigate carefully, get a better view of the channels from a nearby rock, or send scouts ahead in rowboats to see.

children.name: Text
children.value: Find a path through the narrows

children.name: Text
children.value:
To their relief your crew reaches open sea on the other side. As there is a lack of consensus on magnetic north at this time, your navigators decide to ignore the compasses and trust their instincts, saving them a collision on more than one occasion.

The crew enters King William Sound, a majestic carpet of water leading up to its seat, King William Island. Sensing something, Lady Faithful suddenly emerges from below deck, and voices the determined hopes of her heart...

children.name: Text
children.value: The compass readings are confusing. After several wrong turns the crew realise magnetic north is not where they, or anyone else imagined. Your ship finds itself alongside the run-off of a sizeable glacier, which it being spring, is melting. There are cracks, then there is an almighty rumble as the entire wall of ice threatens to separate and topple into the water!

children.name: Text
children.value:
Your crew escape! In moments the masts are dropped almost horizontal to catch every last ounce of wind, and it is just, just enough extra speed to avoid the mountain of ice crashing down into the channel. Waves from this rare natural event form a new avenue leading out to the open sea.

The crew enters King William Sound, a majestic carpet of water leading up to its seat, King William Island. Sensing something, Lady Faithful suddenly emerges from below deck, and voices the determined hopes of her heart...

children.name: Text
children.value:
Your crew escape! The engine room take the initiative ahead of orders the bridge and stoke the fires. The ship picks up just, just enough extra speed to avoid the mountain of ice crashing down into the channel. Waves from this rare natural event form a new avenue leading out to the open sea.

The crew enters King William Sound, a majestic carpet of water leading up to its seat, King William Island. Sensing something, Lady Faithful suddenly emerges from below deck, and voices the determined hopes of her heart...

children.name: Text
children.value:
Your navigators panic. Though the sails catch the breeze, the menfail to adjust out from under the falling wall. Blocks of ice the size of cows tumble onto the deck and explode to powder. A death and several injuries result. The rest are lucky that large waves from the icefall form a new avenue leading out to the open sea.

children.value:

A death and several injuries result. You are lucky that giant waves from the icefall form an avenue of escape out to the open sea.

children.value:

Your ship is no icebreaker. There are cries as blocks of ice the size of cows tumble onto the deck and explode to powder. A death and several injuries result. You are lucky that giant waves from the icefall form an avenue of escape out to the open sea.

children.name: Text
children.value: Send men up the slope for a better view

children.name: Text
children.value:
The men are used to hard climbs like these and are up in no time to survey the labyrinth ahead. They report back with an easy route forward that leads to open sea once more.

The crew enters King William Sound, a majestic carpet of water leading up to its seat, King William Island. Sensing something, Lady Faithful suddenly emerges from below deck, and voices the determined hopes of her heart...

children.name: Text
children.value: Your men say the climb is too steep, or at least, no-one is daredevil enough to attempt it with the limited equipment they have. Everyone is exasperated. You must find another solution.

children.name: Text
children.value: Send scouts ahead in rowboats to check

children.name: Text
children.value:
Follow the seals, that's the answer! Seals and more besides. From their rowboats your scouts are even able to follow a baleen whale as she surfaces for air. She leads them to open water, and your expedition ship follows.

The crew enters King William Sound, a majestic carpet of water leading up to its seat, King William Island. Sensing something, Lady Faithful suddenly emerges from below deck, and voices the determined hopes of her heart...

children.name: Text
children.value: No-one returns with a definitive clue. "Ivory gulls were circling above what looks like a large glacier," says one, "it may lead us to open water..." It's the best you've got, but soon your ship finds itself alongside the run-off of a sizeable glacier, which it being spring, is melting. There are cracks, then there is an almighty rumble as the entire wall of ice threatens to separate and topple into the water!
